node.text:
A 32-year-old murder case that many considered unsolvable has finally been brought to a resolution – and it all came down to the equivalent of just 15 human cells.

While the techniques that made the achievement possible are not new, what made this case truly extraordinary was the amount of DNA that was available: just 0.12 nanograms. That is less than for any case in history – to put the achievement into perspective, the amount of DNA used by commercially available tests is about 750 to 1,000 nanograms.
​
​​​​Read the whole story by clicking on this image post via the link in our bio. 🚀

node.text:
An adult European shag (Phalacrocorax aristotelis) exposing its big erected crest. We’re talking about the bird; behave.

The European shag, also known as a common shag, is a species of cormorant normally found on the rocky coasts of western and southern Europe, North Africa, and southwest Asia. They are one of the deepest divers among the cormorant family, reaching depths as deep as 45 meters when hunting for food.
​
​Image credit: Philippe Clement/Shutterstock, Wolfgang Kruck/Shutterstock.

This tiny adorable guy is a spiny orb-weaver spider!

Measuring around 2-9mm in length, these spiky spiders come in a variety of colors and shapes. There are many different species of spiny orb-weavers, all belonging to the genus Gasteracantha. This one is G. cancriformis, found across the United States, Central America, and the Caribbean.

node.text:
Happy #InternationalTigerDay! Known for being the national animal of India, tigers are the largest cat species in the world, reaching up to 3.3 meters in length and weighing up to 204 kilograms.

International Tiger Day was created to raise awareness for this critically endangered species and what we can do to help them. The population of tigers has dropped by more than 95% since the beginning of the 20th century due to several factors such as illegal wildlife trade and habitat loss.

2022 is the Chinese year of the Tiger, the year the WWF aims to help double the number of wild tigers to over 6,000 by. Currently, there are roughly 3,900 tigers in the wild, with around 3,000 in India.
​
​Image credit: dptro/Shutterstock, Bhanu Tej Prakash/Shutterstock, Ksenya_89/Shutterstock.

node.text:
Ashton Kutcher and Mila Kunis have received some pretty mixed reactions over the last few days after several news outlets reported on their comments that they only bathe their two children when they can actually see the dirt.

Kunis said in an interview with the Armchair Expert podcast that she hadn't been bathed much as a child.

"I didn't have hot water growing up as a child, so I didn't shower much anyway," she said, adding. "But when I had children, I also didn't wash them every day. I wasn't that parent that bathed my newborns – ever."
​
​​​Read the whole story by clicking on this image post via the link in our bio. 🚀

node.text:
Happy #UnderwaterWednesday! Check out the stunning Roboastra gracilis nudibranch!

This small sea slug is found in parts of the West Pacific, and grows up to only around 3cm in length! The horns poking out of its head are called “rhinopores”, and the nudibranch uses these to detect chemical changes in the water around it, allowing them to find food or mates. Very cool!
​
​Image credit: Mike Workman/Shutterstock.

node.text:
Check this out! It’s the caterpillar of a fruit-piercing moth (Eudocima phalonia).

As cute as it looks, it’s considered one of the world’s major fruit pests once fully grown. As adults, the moths use their tough proboscises to extract the juice out of numerous fruit crops. However, in their larval stage, they are mesmerizing to look at. This caterpillar is deterring predators with its defensive pose, bending to raise its eyespots whilst lifting its tail.
​
​Image credit: ananth-tp/Shutterstock

node.text:
A study of wind conditions off Australia's coast indicates a resource that probably exceeds that of the North Sea in speed and reliability. Proposals already exist to tap into this abundant energy, and a new report reveals they could achieve outputs exceeding the highest so far tapped worldwide.
​
​​Read the whole story by clicking on this image post via the link in our bio. 🚀

node.text:
Check out the treehopper (Membracidae)! There are over 3,000 species of treehoppers, insects related to cicadas and leafhoppers. They live on every continent except Antarctica, with only five species known from Europe. Their most prominent feature is the helmet, which comes in a multitude of weird shapes. 

Treehoppers usually live for only a few months, but forever in our nightmares. Yikes.
​
​Image credit: Tran The Ngoc / Shutterstock.

node.text:
This long-legged critter is an arrow crab also known as a spider crab!

They have a triangle-shaped body and extended “snout”, and can be a multitude of colors. Symbiotic relationships have been observed between arrow crabs and squirrelfish and moray eels. Crabs are usually the main food for moray eels and squirrelfish so the relationship was surprising to researchers. The arrow crab species Stenorhynchus seticornis has been seen cleaning several species of moray eels and squirrelfish, and researchers believe other species of reef fish may be potential “clients” too.
​
​Image credit: timsimages.uk / Shutterstock
